Obviously, computers were the answer, and the idea of using them was occasion- ally suggested, starting in the 1960s. But except for experimental software, nothing was built. The psychologists were interested mainly in theories and models. The teachers were interested in immediate signs of suc- cess. The students were cramming to pass their exams. The payo  for genuine progress was somehow too abstract, too delayed, to feed back into the system in a useful way. What was needed was not an academic psy- chologist but a tinkerer, somebody with a lot of time on his hands, a talent for mathemat- ics, and a strangely literal temperament that made him think he should actually recall the things he learn